 First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Adèle was born in 1068. She had at least 2 sons with Giraud Bellay du Montreuil."},"et":{"1068–":"1068–Surnud","1065–1160":"1065–1160","1110–1202":"1110–1202","1112–1187":"1112–1187","1068–Female":"1068–Surnud","1202":"1202","1068":"1068","1112":"1112","1110":"1110","1187":"1187","1065":"1065","1160":"1160","Montreuil Sous Bois, Seine St Denis, France":"Seine-Saint-Denis, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1068–":"1068–Kuollut","1065–1160":"1065–1160","1110–1202":"1110–1202","1112–1187":"1112–1187","1068–Female":"1068–Kuollut","1202":"1202","1068":"1068","1112":"1112","1110":"1110","1187":"1187","1065":"1065","1160":"1160","Montreuil Sous Bois, Seine St Denis, France":"Seine-Saint-Denis, Île-de-France, Ranska"},"fr":{"1068–":"1068–Décédée","1065–1160":"1065–1160","1110–1202":"1110–1202","1112–1187":"1112–1187","1068–Female":"1068–Décédée","1202":"1202","1068":"1068","1112":"1112","1110":"1110","1187":"1187","1065":"1065","1160":"1160","Montreuil Sous Bois, Seine St Denis, France":"Seine-Saint-Denis, Île-de-France, France","lifeSummary":"Adèle est née en 1068. Elle a eu au moins 2 fils avec Giraud Bellay du Montreuil."},"de":{"1068–":"1068–Verstorben","1065–1160":"1065–1160","1110–1202":"1110–1202","1112–1187":"1112–1187","1068–Female":"1068–Verstorben","1202":"1202","1068":"1068","1112":"1112","1110":"1110","1187":"1187","1065":"1065","1160":"1160","Montreuil Sous Bois, Seine St Denis, France":"Seine-Saint-Denis, Île-de-France, Frankreich","lifeSummary":"Adèle wurde 1068 geboren. Sie hatte mit Giraud Bellay du Montreuil mindestens 2 Söhne."},"ht":{"1068–":"1068–Desede","1065–1160":"1065–1160","1110–1202":"1110–1202","1112–1187":"1112–1187","1068–Female":"1068–Desede","1202":"1202","1068":"1068","11